{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492415"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1056"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1056"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.17,0.38,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80616"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1056"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35698"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80616"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of vague and intermittent upper abdominal pain. She immigrated from Syria five years ago. She has recently developed episodes of fever and chills. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild right upper quadrant tenderness without peritonism. Computed tomography reveals three large cysts in liver segments 4 and 6 with visible daughter cysts (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and follow-up","Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Broad spectrum antibiotics","Percutaneous aspiration and albendazole","Surgical resection with albendazole"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe imaging findings of multiple hepatic cysts with daughter cysts in a patient from an endemic region are characteristic of hydatid disease, caused by the \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus\u003C/em\u003E tapeworm. Given the patient\u0027s symptoms and high-risk features (multiple cysts \u003E10cm, age \u003E40), intervention is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical resection\u003C/strong\u003E with perioperative albendazole remains the gold standard treatment, offering the lowest recurrence rates. This can be performed laparoscopically or open, typically with albendazole 400mg twice daily for one week before and four weeks after surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E with albendazole is a potential alternative but carries risks of cyst rupture, fluid leakage, and disease recurrence. It may be considered in patients who are poor surgical candidates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is absolutely contraindicated in suspected hydatid disease due to the risk of cyst rupture leading to anaphylaxis and peritoneal dissemination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroad spectrum antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate as they do not address the underlying parasitic infection. While antibiotics may be needed if secondary bacterial infection is present, they are not the definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the patient\u0027s symptoms and high-risk features. Watch-and-wait approaches are reserved for small, asymptomatic cysts in low-risk patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Surgical resection remains the gold standard treatment for symptomatic hepatic hydatid cysts, particularly with high-risk features (size \u003E10cm, multiple cysts, age \u003E40).","Hydatid disease should be suspected in patients from endemic regions presenting with liver cysts.","Fine needle aspiration is contraindicated in suspected hydatid disease due to risk of anaphylaxis and dissemination."],"references":["Higuita NIA, Brunetti E, McCloskey C. Cystic echinococcis. J Clin Micro. 2016; 54:518-23."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1056"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18647"},{"type":"media","id":"18648"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18647"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e368fc33-2e5f-4b30-aec3-8ea7625dfcb9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e368fc33-2e5f-4b30-aec3-8ea7625dfcb9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":432,"height":343}},{"type":"media","id":"18648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18648"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0c1dd88c-1883-4717-aef0-31c5ae02f4e2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0c1dd88c-1883-4717-aef0-31c5ae02f4e2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":338,"height":447}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T21:07:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T21:08:45+10:30"},